The paper deals with compressive sensing theory and its applications, specifically focusing on the impact of quantization of signal measurements on signal reconstruction. This falls under the information theory (cs.IT) and signal processing (cs.SP) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of random matrices that respect the restricted isometry property (RIP), which is a topic in machine learning (cs.LG) and matrix methods (cs.MM). Finally, the paper presents empirical results on various sensing contexts, which could fall under the numerical analysis (cs.NA) sub-category.
